{{Infobox artwork | title = Farewell to Orpheus | other_language_1 = | other_title_1 = | other_language_2 = | other_title_2 = | image_file = File:Farewell to Orpheus sculpture, Portland, Oregon.jpg | image_size = | alt = | caption = The sculpture and fountain in 2015 | artist = Frederic Littman | catalogue = | year = 1968–1973 | completion_date = <!-- For a more specific date (post-1583): {{start date|YYYY|MM|DD|df=y}} --> | type = {{Flatlist| * Sculpture * fountain }} | material = [[Bronze sculpture|Bronze]] | subject = [[Eurydice]] | height_metric = <!-- (i.e. in metric units) --> | width_metric = | length_metric = | diameter_metric = | height_imperial = <!-- (i.e. in imperial units) --> | width_imperial = | length_imperial = | diameter_imperial = | dimensions = | dimensions_ref = | metric_unit = cm <!-- Note: this parameter must either use the value given or not be included --> | imperial_unit = in <!-- Note: this parameter must either use the value given or not be included --> | condition = | city = [[Portland, Oregon]], United States | museum = | accession = | coordinates = {{coord|45.5124|-122.6848|display=inline,title}} | pushpin_map = Portland State University OR | pushpin_mapsize = | pushpin_map_caption = Location on the [[Portland State University]] campus | pushpin_label_position = | owner = [[Portland State University]] | url = <!-- Official webpage/site only: {{URL|example.com}} --> }} '''''Farewell to Orpheus''''' is an outdoor 1968–1973 [[bronze sculpture]] and fountain by [[Frederic Littman]], installed at the [[Portland State University]] campus in [[Portland, Oregon]], United States.
==Description and history== [[File:Farewell to Orpheus plaque, 2015.jpg|thumb|left|upright|Plaque for the sculpture]]
''Farewell to Orpheus'', created by former [[Portland State University]] (PSU) art professor [[Frederic Littman]] in 1968,<ref name=SI>{{cite web|title=Farewell to Orpheus, (sculpture).|url=http://siris-artinventories.si.edu/ipac20/ipac.jsp?&profile=all&source=~!siartinventories&uri=full=3100001~!368903~!0#focus|publisher=[[Smithsonian Institution]]|accessdate=April 1, 2015}}</ref><ref name=LaDu>{{Cite web|url=http://www.pdx.edu/facilities/sites/www.pdx.edu.facilities/files/POSTED%20Article%20Littman%20Fountain.pdf |title=Littman Sculpture and Fountain in the Park Blocks |format=PDF |first=John |last=LaDu |publisher=[[Portland State University]] |accessdate=April 1, 2015 |df= }}{{dead link|date=April 2017|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref> is located at Southwest Montgomery Street in the [[South Park Blocks]].<ref name=SPB>{{cite web|title=South Park Blocks|url=http://www.portlandoregon.gov/parks/finder/index.cfm?&propertyid=674&action=ViewPark|publisher=[[Portland Parks & Recreation]]|accessdate=April 1, 2015}}</ref><ref name=Cook>{{cite book|last=Cook|first=Sybilla Avery|title=Walking Portland|year=1998|publisher=[[Globe Pequot Press]]|page=66|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=oh_dA76n37gC&pg=PA66&lpg=PA66&dq#v=onepage&q&f=false|accessdate=April 1, 2015}}</ref> It depicts [[Eurydice]] and was installed in 1972–1973 as part of the South Park Blocks Urban Renewal Development Project.<ref name=SI/><ref name=LaDu/><ref name=SPB/> The fountain is one of four maintained by PSU, along with ''Walk of Heroines'' at Hoffman Hall, another in front of the Student Health and Counseling Building, and one at Urban Plaza.<ref name=SI/><ref name=Hannan>{{cite news|last1=Hannan|first1=Jor|title=Are fountains folly?|url=http://psuvanguard.com/uncategorized/are-fountains-folly/|accessdate=April 1, 2015|work=[[Daily Vanguard]]|publisher=Portland State University|date=May 26, 2010}}</ref>
The sculpture has always been surrounded by water but the fountain, which continually recycles 227 gallons of water, was not added until the 1990s. In 2009, PSU partnered with the City of Portland and the sculpture's owners to repair the fountain, which had not worked for nearly a decade. Repairs cost $6,000 and were funded in part by rentals on the South Park Blocks. Work included installation of new fountain heads, lights, and wiring, and re-sealing underwater surfaces. The repairs were completed by three PSU employees.<ref name=LaDu/> ''Farewell to Orpheus'' has been described as a "seating refuge" for students and included in published walking tours of the city.<ref name=Cook/><ref name=SMGS>{{cite web|title=The Southwest Montgomery Green Street: Connecting the West Hills with the Willamette River|url=https://www.portlandoregon.gov/bes/article/313935|accessdate=April 1, 2015|date=October 2009|pages=8, 24–25|publisher=City of Portland, Oregon|format=PDF}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last1=Cook|first1=Sybilla Avery|title=Walking Portland, Oregon|date=April 2, 2013|publisher=[[Rowman & Littlefield]]|page=46|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=wvPWSWqzCT0C&pg=PA46&lpg=PA46&dq#v=onepage&q&f=false|accessdate=April 1, 2015}}</ref>
