[[File:Meister der Josephsfolge 002.jpg|thumb|160px|Joseph and Asenath together on this image in [[Berlin]]. Man depicted close to them may be Potipherah.]] '''Potipherah''' {{IPAc-en|p|ɒ|ˈ|t|ɪ|f|ər|ə}} was a priest of the [[Ancient Egypt]]ian town of [[On (Ancient Egypt)|On]],<ref>The Open court , Volume 27. Harry Houdini Collection (Library of Congress).</ref> mentioned in the {{bibleverse||Genesis|41:45|HE}} and {{bibleverse-nb||Genesis|41:50|HE}}.
He was the father of [[Asenath]], who was given to [[Joseph (son of Jacob)|Joseph]] as his wife by [[Pharaoh]], ({{bibleverse-nb||Genesis|41:45|HE}}) and who bore Joseph two sons: [[Manasseh (tribal patriarch)|Manasseh]] and [[Ephraim]].<ref>{{bibleverse-nb||Genesis|41:50|HE}}</ref>
His name means "he whom [[Ra]] has given".{{citation needed|date=November 2016}}
== Theories == It was suggested that Potipherah was a prince, not only a priest,<ref>[https://books.google.com/booksid=F9ksAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA70&dq=potipherah&hl=en&sa=X&ei=kBz4T4OmNMX_4QTi6jcBg&ved=0CC4Q6AEwAA#v=onepage&q=potipherah&f=false A Concise Dictionary of the Bible for the Use of Families and Students by William Aldis Wright, Edmonds & Remnants]</ref> and that he may be the same person as [[Potiphar]].
If this is true, then the wife of Potipherah was in love with Joseph, as it is said for [[Zuleika (legendary)|Potiphar's wife]].<ref>Legends of Old Testament characters from the Talmud and other sources by Sabine Baring-Gould</ref>
== Sources == {{quote|And Pharaoh called Joseph's name Zaphnathpaaneah; and he gave him to wife [[Asenath]] the daughter of Potipherah priest of On. And Joseph went out over [all] the land of Egypt.|Genesis 41:45, [[KJV]] 1611}}
